05114nam a22006375i 9780823290918DE-B159720220329044247.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220329t20222005nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232909187 a10.1515/97808232909182doi  a(DE-B1597)566094  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aHIS0271002bisacsh1 aDietrich, Frank, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aArmy GI, Pacifist CO :bThe World War II Letters of Frank Dietrich and Albert Dietrich /cFrank Dietrich, Albert Dietrich; ed. by Scott H. Bennett. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2022] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (408 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aWorld War II: The Global, Human, and Ethical Dimension00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote from the Editor -- tList of Abbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1: 1939–42: “Aren’t We Faced with the Choice of a Lesser of Two Evils?” -- tChapter 2: 1943: “Crimes Against Humanity”? -- tChapter 3: 1944: “Camp Life” -- tChapter 4: 1945: “The Devastation and Destruction Is Positively Staggering” -- tChapter 5: 1946: “The FOR . . . Is Realistic and Activist” -- tAppendix A: Albert G. Dietrich, Sample Form 47 -- tAppendix B: Albert G. Dietrich, Request for Presidential Appeal by Conscientious Objector [June 1943] -- tAppendix C: Daily Schedule and Rules for CPS Camps Administered by the Mennonite Central Committee -- tAppendix D: Albert Dietrich to Frank and Christine Dietrich, 1986 -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrank and Albert Dietrich were identical twins whose lives took very different directions during World War II. Drafted into the Army Air Corps and trained as a radio operator, Frank was shipped to the Philippines in 1945, where as a sergeant in the Fifth Air Force he prepared for the invasion of Japan. Albert, a pacifist, struggled mightily to become a conscientious objector and spent two years building dams, saving farmland, and helping the poor at Civilian Service Camps in South Dakota, Iowa, and Florida. Raised in a close, religious, Pittsburgh family, Frank and Albert were inseparable as boys, sharing a strong social conscience. Divided by war, they kept in touch by writing hundreds of letters to each other. The correspondence concerns everything from the daily drudgery of service—loneliness, lousy food—to heartfelt debates about war, peace, and patriotism. This absorbing selection of letters offers fresh perspectives on the American experience during World War II. The first published correspondence between GI and CO brothers, the letters are an uncommonly articulate chronicle of military service and life on the home front, including GI marriage and parenthood. Back and forth, Frank and Albert also argued about the uses of armed force and pacifist nonviolence in the face of fascism and Nazism. Frank Dietrich’s letters from Manila are vivid descriptions of a liberated city under an uneasy occupation. Albert provides an insider’s view of the pacifist experience, especially the protracted efforts pacifists often had to wage to obtain CO status. Together, the letters bring to life different ways Americans chose to serve their country during one of its most dangerous and demanding times.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 7aHISTORY / Military / World War II.2bisacsh1 aBennett, Scott H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBennett, Scott H., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDietrich, Albert, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000